<paragraph id="2576369FFFDAE67DCFDFFCD7372CFAE9" blockId="5.[151,1436,769,2026]" pageId="5" pageNumber="266">
The largest and the most diverse subgenus of 
<taxonomicName id="E2C94D1CFFDAE67DCDEDFCD73159FCF5" authorityName="Bílý" authorityYear="2019" box="[677,778,769,794]" class="Insecta" family="Buprestidae" genus="Anthaxia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="5" pageNumber="266" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="17BDEA8DFFDAE67DCDEDFCD73159FCF5" box="[677,778,769,794]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="266">Anthaxia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. Usually small to medium-sized species (3.5–9.0 mm) of metallic colouration ranging from the black-bronze to bright green or multicolorous species (
<figureCitation id="BDF22A1AFFDAE67DCB86FCF23718FCD2" box="[1230,1355,804,829]" captionStart="FIGURES 1–12" captionStartId="9.[151,264,1854,1877]" captionTargetBox="[160,1426,239,1794]" captionTargetId="figure@9.[151,1436,230,1801]" captionTargetPageId="9" captionText="FIGURES 1–12. Anthaxia, dorsal aspect. 1—Anthaxia (Anthaxia) fulgurans (Schrank), male, 4.5 mm; 2—A. (A.) plicata plicata Kiesenwetter, female, 5.1 mm; 3—A. (A.) salicis salicis (Fabricius), male, 4.1 mm; 4—A. (A.) malachitica Abeille, male, 2.1 mm; 5—A. (A.) stepanovi Richter, holotype, 3.0 mm; 6—A. (Cratomerus) hungarica hungarica (Scopoli), male, 12.0 mm; 7—the same, female, 13.5 mm; 8—A. (Haplanthaxia) dispar Kerremans, male, 7.5 mm; 9—A. (H.) cichorii (Olivier), male, 5.1 mm; 10—A. (H.) kneuckeri zabranskyi Bílý, male, 5.1 mm; 11—A. (A.) cashmirensis Obenberger, male, 8.5 mm; 12—A. (Melanthaxia) godeti Gory &amp; Laporte, male, 4.7 mm." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/2599420/files/figure.png" pageId="5" pageNumber="266">Figs. 8–10</figureCitation>
), often with black pronotal stripes or (rarely) with dark elytral pattern; frons flat, weakly depressed or rarely somewhat convex, vertex 0.5–2.5 times as wide as width of eye; antennae of male not or only weakly enlarged; pronotum moderately convex or flat, lateroposterior depressions shallow to deep and wide, anterior third of lateral margins weakly or very weakly rounded (
<figureCitation id="BDF22A1AFFDAE67DCD5CFC6730F3FC25" box="[532,672,945,970]" captionStart="FIGURES 40–54" captionStartId="12.[151,264,1837,1860]" captionTargetBox="[165,1425,353,1806]" captionTargetId="figure@12.[151,1435,339,1815]" captionTargetPageId="12" captionText="FIGURES 40–54. Anthaxia, pronotal sculpture (not in scale). 40—Anthaxia (Anthaxia) fulgurans (Schrank); 41—A. (A.) salicis salicis (Fabricius); 42—A. (A.) manca (Fabricius); 43—A. (Melanthaxia) nigrojubata nigrojubata Roubal; 44—A. (Cratomerus) hungarica hungarica (Scopoli); 45—A. (Haplanthaxia) cichorii (Olivier); 46—A. (H.) kneuckeri zabranskyi Bílý; 47—A. (H.) pumila (Klug); 48—A. (Richteraxia) angustipennis (Klug); 49—A. (R.) marginifera metallescens Bílý; 50— A. (Merocratus) tamdaoensis Bílý; 51—A. (Thailandia) rondoni Baudon; 52—A. (Capanthaxia) capensis Kerremans; 53—A. (Cap.) aterrima Kerremans; 54—A. (Cap.) sulcicollis Obenberger." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/2599428/files/figure.png" pageId="5" pageNumber="266">Figs. 45–47</figureCitation>
); posterior pronotal angles obtuse-angled or less often rectangular; sculpture usually consisting of rounded or polygonal cells (with or without central grains) which are sometimes transversely widened and combined with fine, transverse rugae, or fine, lateral, longitudinal wrinkles (
<figureCitation id="BDF22A1AFFDAE67DCA70FC2137DCFBFF" box="[1336,1423,1015,1040]" captionStart="FIGURES 40–54" captionStartId="12.[151,264,1837,1860]" captionTargetBox="[165,1425,353,1806]" captionTargetId="figure@12.[151,1435,339,1815]" captionTargetPageId="12" captionText="FIGURES 40–54. Anthaxia, pronotal sculpture (not in scale). 40—Anthaxia (Anthaxia) fulgurans (Schrank); 41—A. (A.) salicis salicis (Fabricius); 42—A. (A.) manca (Fabricius); 43—A. (Melanthaxia) nigrojubata nigrojubata Roubal; 44—A. (Cratomerus) hungarica hungarica (Scopoli); 45—A. (Haplanthaxia) cichorii (Olivier); 46—A. (H.) kneuckeri zabranskyi Bílý; 47—A. (H.) pumila (Klug); 48—A. (Richteraxia) angustipennis (Klug); 49—A. (R.) marginifera metallescens Bílý; 50— A. (Merocratus) tamdaoensis Bílý; 51—A. (Thailandia) rondoni Baudon; 52—A. (Capanthaxia) capensis Kerremans; 53—A. (Cap.) aterrima Kerremans; 54—A. (Cap.) sulcicollis Obenberger." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/2599428/files/figure.png" pageId="5" pageNumber="266">Fig. 46</figureCitation>
); only rarely pronotal sculpture consisting only of rounded cells (
<figureCitation id="BDF22A1AFFDAE67DCCCFFBCC318EFBDC" box="[903,989,1050,1075]" captionStart="FIGURES 40–54" captionStartId="12.[151,264,1837,1860]" captionTargetBox="[165,1425,353,1806]" captionTargetId="figure@12.[151,1435,339,1815]" captionTargetPageId="12" captionText="FIGURES 40–54. Anthaxia, pronotal sculpture (not in scale). 40—Anthaxia (Anthaxia) fulgurans (Schrank); 41—A. (A.) salicis salicis (Fabricius); 42—A. (A.) manca (Fabricius); 43—A. (Melanthaxia) nigrojubata nigrojubata Roubal; 44—A. (Cratomerus) hungarica hungarica (Scopoli); 45—A. (Haplanthaxia) cichorii (Olivier); 46—A. (H.) kneuckeri zabranskyi Bílý; 47—A. (H.) pumila (Klug); 48—A. (Richteraxia) angustipennis (Klug); 49—A. (R.) marginifera metallescens Bílý; 50— A. (Merocratus) tamdaoensis Bílý; 51—A. (Thailandia) rondoni Baudon; 52—A. (Capanthaxia) capensis Kerremans; 53—A. (Cap.) aterrima Kerremans; 54—A. (Cap.) sulcicollis Obenberger." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/2599428/files/figure.png" pageId="5" pageNumber="266">Fig. 45</figureCitation>
) or simple punctures (
<figureCitation id="BDF22A1AFFDAE67DCBA3FBCC3717FBDC" box="[1259,1348,1050,1075]" captionStart="FIGURES 40–54" captionStartId="12.[151,264,1837,1860]" captionTargetBox="[165,1425,353,1806]" captionTargetId="figure@12.[151,1435,339,1815]" captionTargetPageId="12" captionText="FIGURES 40–54. Anthaxia, pronotal sculpture (not in scale). 40—Anthaxia (Anthaxia) fulgurans (Schrank); 41—A. (A.) salicis salicis (Fabricius); 42—A. (A.) manca (Fabricius); 43—A. (Melanthaxia) nigrojubata nigrojubata Roubal; 44—A. (Cratomerus) hungarica hungarica (Scopoli); 45—A. (Haplanthaxia) cichorii (Olivier); 46—A. (H.) kneuckeri zabranskyi Bílý; 47—A. (H.) pumila (Klug); 48—A. (Richteraxia) angustipennis (Klug); 49—A. (R.) marginifera metallescens Bílý; 50— A. (Merocratus) tamdaoensis Bílý; 51—A. (Thailandia) rondoni Baudon; 52—A. (Capanthaxia) capensis Kerremans; 53—A. (Cap.) aterrima Kerremans; 54—A. (Cap.) sulcicollis Obenberger." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/2599428/files/figure.png" pageId="5" pageNumber="266">Fig. 47</figureCitation>
); elytra usually regularly convex, moderately tapering posteriorly or almost subcylindrical, usually only 3 (4) abdominal ventrites easily visible from above (
<figureCitation id="BDF22A1AFFDAE67DCD7EFBB730E0FB96" box="[566,691,1121,1146]" captionStart="FIGURES 1–12" captionStartId="9.[151,264,1854,1877]" captionTargetBox="[160,1426,239,1794]" captionTargetId="figure@9.[151,1436,230,1801]" captionTargetPageId="9" captionText="FIGURES 1–12. Anthaxia, dorsal aspect. 1—Anthaxia (Anthaxia) fulgurans (Schrank), male, 4.5 mm; 2—A. (A.) plicata plicata Kiesenwetter, female, 5.1 mm; 3—A. (A.) salicis salicis (Fabricius), male, 4.1 mm; 4—A. (A.) malachitica Abeille, male, 2.1 mm; 5—A. (A.) stepanovi Richter, holotype, 3.0 mm; 6—A. (Cratomerus) hungarica hungarica (Scopoli), male, 12.0 mm; 7—the same, female, 13.5 mm; 8—A. (Haplanthaxia) dispar Kerremans, male, 7.5 mm; 9—A. (H.) cichorii (Olivier), male, 5.1 mm; 10—A. (H.) kneuckeri zabranskyi Bílý, male, 5.1 mm; 11—A. (A.) cashmirensis Obenberger, male, 8.5 mm; 12—A. (Melanthaxia) godeti Gory &amp; Laporte, male, 4.7 mm." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/2599420/files/figure.png" pageId="5" pageNumber="266">Figs. 9–10</figureCitation>
); anal ventrite of female usually apically notched or emarginate, rarely rounded; aedeagus of various shapes, and almost all 
<typeStatus id="FA72883DFFDAE67DCC70FB533120FB72" box="[824,883,1157,1181]" pageId="5" pageNumber="266">types</typeStatus>
of aedeagus known in 
<taxonomicName id="E2C94D1CFFDAE67DCB35FB5236B0FB72" authorityName="Bílý" authorityYear="2019" box="[1149,1251,1156,1181]" class="Insecta" family="Buprestidae" genus="Anthaxia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="5" pageNumber="266" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="17BDEA8DFFDAE67DCB35FB5236B0FB72" box="[1149,1251,1156,1181]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="266">Anthaxia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
can be found in this subgenus: tubuliform, spindle-shaped, flattened, widened or subcylindrical, quite exceptionally asymmetric (
<figureCitation id="BDF22A1AFFDAE67DCFD7FB1C3379FB0C" box="[159,298,1226,1251]" captionStart="FIGURES 55–76" captionStartId="15.[151,264,1812,1835]" captionTargetBox="[155,1426,217,1762]" captionTargetId="figure@15.[150,1436,203,1771]" captionTargetPageId="15" captionText="FIGURES 55–76. Anthaxia, aedeagi (not in scale). 55—Anthaxia (Anthaxia) candens (Panzer); 56—A. (A.) kmoniceki Bílý; 57—A. (Melanthaxia) nigrojubata incognita Bílý; 58—A. (M.) helvetica Stierlin; 59—A. (M.) obesa Abeille; 60—A. (Cratomerus) hungarica hungarica (Scopoli); 61—A. (Richteraxia) angustipennis (Klug); 62—A. (R.) crassa Obenberger; 63—A. (R.) imperatrix Obenberger; 64—A. (Haplanthaxia) elaeagni Richter; 65—A. (H.) nigroaenea Bílý; 66—A. (H.) pseudocongregata Descarpentries; 67—A. (H.) kneuckeri zabranskyi Bílý; 68—A. (H.) deimos Bílý; 69—A. (H.) dispar Kerremans; 70—A. (H.) loebli Bílý; 71—A. (H.) thailandica Bílý; 72—A. (H.) occulta Bílý; 73—A. (H.) duodevicesima Bílý; 74—A. (Merocratus) longipilis Bílý; 75—A. (Thailandica) rondoni; 76—A. (Capanthaxia) capensis Kerremans." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/2599430/files/figure.png" pageId="5" pageNumber="266">Figs. 64–73</figureCitation>
); parameres often with lateral spines, median lobe often with serrate lateral margins. Tarsal claws in some species with large basal tooth (
<emphasis id="17BDEA8DFFDAE67DCD7AFB383010FAEA" box="[562,579,1262,1285]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="266">A</emphasis>
. (
<emphasis id="17BDEA8DFFDAE67DCD13FB39303CFAE9" box="[603,623,1263,1286]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="266">H</emphasis>
.) 
<emphasis id="17BDEA8DFFDAE67DCDCEFB3B3088FAE9" box="[646,731,1261,1286]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="266">collaris</emphasis>
species-group and some Afrotropical and Nearctic species).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="6DD36514FFDAE67DCF8FFAC73009FA35" pageId="5" pageNumber="266" type="description">
<paragraph id="2576369FFFDAE67DCF8FFAC736C1FA7C" blockId="5.[151,1436,769,2026]" pageId="5" pageNumber="266">
Some species of this subgenus have very often been placed in the subgenus 
<emphasis id="17BDEA8DFFDAE67DCB6CFAC436E3FAC6" box="[1060,1200,1298,1321]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="266">
<taxonomicName id="E2C94D1CFFDAE67DCB6CFAC436FEFAC6" authorityName="Solier" authorityYear="1833" box="[1060,1197,1298,1321]" class="Insecta" family="Buprestidae" genus="Anthaxia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="5" pageNumber="266" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="subGenus" subGenus="Cratomerus">Cratomerus</taxonomicName>
,
</emphasis>
but it seems that the most related subgenus is 
<taxonomicName id="E2C94D1CFFDAE67DCEFAFAE23066FAA2" authority="Bílý, 2019" authorityName="Bílý" authorityYear="2019" box="[434,565,1332,1357]" class="Insecta" family="Buprestidae" genus="Anthaxia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="5" pageNumber="266" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="subGenus" status="subgen. nov." subGenus="Richteraxia">
<emphasis id="17BDEA8DFFDAE67DCEFAFAE23066FAA2" box="[434,565,1332,1357]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="266">Richteraxia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<emphasis id="17BDEA8DFFDAE67DCD74FAE2309CFAA3" bold="true" box="[572,719,1332,1356]" pageId="5" pageNumber="266">
<taxonomicNameLabel id="0C8E57F6FFDAE67DCD74FAE2309CFAA3" box="[572,719,1332,1356]" pageId="5" pageNumber="266" rank="subGenus">subgen. nov.</taxonomicNameLabel>
</emphasis>
The division between both subgenera is rather unclear; the best diagnostic characters seems to be the form of the pronotum and its sculpture, as well as the shape and sculpture of elytra and the form of male metatibiae and antennae (see 
<taxonomicName id="E2C94D1CFFDAE67DCC51FAAC31CFFA7C" authority="Bílý, 2019" authorityName="Bílý" authorityYear="2019" box="[793,924,1402,1427]" class="Insecta" family="Buprestidae" genus="Anthaxia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="5" pageNumber="266" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="subGenus" status="subgen. nov." subGenus="Richteraxia">
<emphasis id="17BDEA8DFFDAE67DCC51FAAC31CFFA7C" box="[793,924,1402,1427]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="266">Richteraxia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<emphasis id="17BDEA8DFFDAE67DCCEBFAAD3665FA7C" bold="true" box="[931,1078,1403,1427]" pageId="5" pageNumber="266">
<taxonomicNameLabel id="0C8E57F6FFDAE67DCCEBFAAD3665FA7C" box="[931,1078,1403,1427]" pageId="5" pageNumber="266" rank="subGenus">subgen. nov.</taxonomicNameLabel>
</emphasis>
below).
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="2576369FFFDAE67DCF8FFA493009FA35" blockId="5.[151,1436,769,2026]" pageId="5" pageNumber="266">
BIONOMY. Development in Conifers, broad-leaved trees and shrubs, and also in herbs (some South African species are associated with 
<taxonomicName id="E2C94D1CFFDAE67DCE83FA17301DFA35" authorityName="" authorityYear="1789" box="[459,590,1473,1498]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Solanaceae" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Plantae" order="Solanales" pageId="5" pageNumber="266" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="family">Solanaceae</taxonomicName>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="6DD36514FFDAE67ECF8FFA333065FEAF" lastPageId="6" lastPageNumber="267" pageId="5" pageNumber="266" type="distribution">
<paragraph id="2576369FFFDAE67DCF8FFA333735FA13" blockId="5.[151,1436,769,2026]" box="[199,1382,1508,1533]" pageId="5" pageNumber="266">
DISTRIBUTION: entire distribution of the genus 
<taxonomicName id="E2C94D1CFFDAE67DCD9DFA323169FA12" authorityName="Bílý" authorityYear="2019" box="[725,826,1508,1533]" class="Insecta" family="Buprestidae" genus="Anthaxia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="5" pageNumber="266" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="17BDEA8DFFDAE67DCD9DFA323169FA12" box="[725,826,1508,1533]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="266">Anthaxia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
except for the northern parts of Asia and Europe.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="2576369FFFDAE67DCF8FF9DE3391F8B3" blockId="5.[151,1436,769,2026]" pageId="5" pageNumber="266">
