<taxonomicName id="E2C94D1CFFDAE67DCB18F8F73680F8D5" authority="Bílý, 2019" authorityName="Bílý" authorityYear="2019" box="[1104,1235,1825,1850]" class="Insecta" family="Buprestidae" genus="Anthaxia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="5" pageNumber="266" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="subGenus" status="subgen. nov." subGenus="Richteraxia">
<emphasis id="17BDEA8DFFDAE67DCB18F8F73680F8D5" box="[1104,1235,1825,1850]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="266">Richteraxia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<emphasis id="17BDEA8DFFDAE67DCB97F8F7372BF8D6" bold="true" box="[1247,1400,1825,1849]" pageId="5" pageNumber="266">
<taxonomicNameLabel id="0C8E57F6FFDAE67DCB97F8F7372BF8D6" box="[1247,1400,1825,1849]" pageId="5" pageNumber="266" rank="subGenus">subgen. nov.</taxonomicNameLabel>
</emphasis>
or 
<taxonomicName id="E2C94D1CFFDAE67DCFDFF892337BF8B2" authority="Bílý, 2019" authorityName="Bílý" authorityYear="2019" box="[151,296,1860,1885]" class="Insecta" family="Buprestidae" genus="Anthaxia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="5" pageNumber="266" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="subGenus" status="subgen. nov." subGenus="Capanthaxia">
<emphasis id="17BDEA8DFFDAE67DCFDFF892337BF8B2" box="[151,296,1860,1885]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="266">Capanthaxia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<emphasis id="17BDEA8DFFDAE67DCE66F8923391F8B3" bold="true" box="[302,450,1860,1884]" pageId="5" pageNumber="266">
<taxonomicNameLabel id="0C8E57F6FFDAE67DCE66F8923391F8B3" box="[302,450,1860,1884]" pageId="5" pageNumber="266" rank="subGenus">subgen. nov.</taxonomicNameLabel>
</emphasis>
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="2576369FFFDAE67DCF8FF8B13173F805" blockId="5.[151,1436,769,2026]" pageId="5" pageNumber="266">
All species of the 
<taxonomicName id="E2C94D1CFFDAE67DCED3F8BE300AF86F" authorityName="Obenberger" authorityYear="1931" box="[411,601,1895,1920]" class="Insecta" family="Buprestidae" genus="Anthaxia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="5" pageNumber="266" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="mashuna" subGenus="Haplanthaxia">
<emphasis id="17BDEA8DFFDAE67DCED3F8BE33E0F890" box="[411,435,1896,1919]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="266">A.</emphasis>
(
<emphasis id="17BDEA8DFFDAE67DCE8EF8BE33B1F890" box="[454,482,1896,1919]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="266">H.</emphasis>
) 
<emphasis id="17BDEA8DFFDAE67DCEBCF8B1300AF86F" box="[500,601,1895,1920]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="266">mashuna</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
species-group (and a few, similar species from the southernmost part of Africa) possess only weakly developed subhumeral lobe (
<figureCitation id="BDF22A1AFFDAE67DCC57F85C3122F84C" box="[799,881,1930,1955]" captionStart="FIGURES 25–39" captionStartId="11.[151,264,1832,1855]" captionTargetBox="[159,1427,742,1802]" captionTargetId="figure@11.[150,1437,733,1811]" captionTargetPageId="11" captionText="FIGURES 25–39. Anthaxia, subhumeral lobe (not in scale). 25—Anthaxia (Richteraxia) amplithorax Kerremans, white arrow indicates “lock&quot; in humeral callosity; 26—A. (Anthaxia) salicis salicis (Fabricius); 27—A. (A.) fulgurans (Schrank); 28—A. (A.) plicata plicata Kiesenwetter; 29—A. (A.) stepanovi Richter, holotype; 30—A. (Cratomerus) hungarica hungarica (Scopoli); 31—A. (Haplanthaxia) cichorii (Olivier); 32—A. (H.) caseyi Obenberger; 33—A. (H.) dispar Kerremans; 34—A. (Richteraxia) angustipennis (Klug); 35—A. (Melanthaxia) quadripunctata (Linnaeus); 36—A. (M.) kochi Obenberger; 37—A. (Merocratus) insulaecola Obenberger; 38—A. (Thailandia.) rondoni Baudon; 39—A. (Capanthzaxia..) hilaris Gory." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/2599424/files/figure.png" pageId="5" pageNumber="266">Fig. 33</figureCitation>
) so that they could be interpreted as belonging to 
<taxonomicName id="E2C94D1CFFDAE67DCFDFF87B32AFF829" authority="Bílý, 2019" authorityName="Bílý" authorityYear="2019" box="[151,252,1965,1990]" class="Insecta" family="Buprestidae" genus="Anthaxia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="5" pageNumber="266" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus" sensu="stricto" status="s. str.">
<emphasis id="17BDEA8DFFDAE67DCFDFF87B32AFF829" box="[151,252,1965,1990]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="266">Anthaxia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel id="0C8E57F6FFDAE67DCE4BF8793313F829" box="[259,320,1967,1990]" pageId="5" pageNumber="266" sensu="stricto">s. str.</taxonomicNameLabel>
, but all other characters correspond to the subgenus 
<emphasis id="17BDEA8DFFDAE67DCCC6F87B367CF829" box="[910,1071,1965,1990]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="266">
<taxonomicName id="E2C94D1CFFDAE67DCCC6F87B3678F829" authorityName="Reitter" authorityYear="1911" box="[910,1067,1965,1990]" class="Insecta" family="Buprestidae" genus="Anthaxia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="5" pageNumber="266" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="subGenus" subGenus="Haplanthaxia">Haplanthaxia</taxonomicName>
,
</emphasis>
namely the shape of elytra (
<figureCitation id="BDF22A1AFFDAE67DCA26F87B32F6F806" captionStart="FIGURES 1–12" captionStartId="9.[151,264,1854,1877]" captionTargetBox="[160,1426,239,1794]" captionTargetId="figure@9.[151,1436,230,1801]" captionTargetPageId="9" captionText="FIGURES 1–12. Anthaxia, dorsal aspect. 1—Anthaxia (Anthaxia) fulgurans (Schrank), male, 4.5 mm; 2—A. (A.) plicata plicata Kiesenwetter, female, 5.1 mm; 3—A. (A.) salicis salicis (Fabricius), male, 4.1 mm; 4—A. (A.) malachitica Abeille, male, 2.1 mm; 5—A. (A.) stepanovi Richter, holotype, 3.0 mm; 6—A. (Cratomerus) hungarica hungarica (Scopoli), male, 12.0 mm; 7—the same, female, 13.5 mm; 8—A. (Haplanthaxia) dispar Kerremans, male, 7.5 mm; 9—A. (H.) cichorii (Olivier), male, 5.1 mm; 10—A. (H.) kneuckeri zabranskyi Bílý, male, 5.1 mm; 11—A. (A.) cashmirensis Obenberger, male, 8.5 mm; 12—A. (Melanthaxia) godeti Gory &amp; Laporte, male, 4.7 mm." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/2599420/files/figure.png" pageId="5" pageNumber="266">Fig. 8</figureCitation>
) and extraordinary form of the male genitalia (
<figureCitation id="BDF22A1AFFDAE67DCDFDF8073147F805" box="[693,788,2001,2026]" captionStart="FIGURES 55–76" captionStartId="15.[151,264,1812,1835]" captionTargetBox="[155,1426,217,1762]" captionTargetId="figure@15.[150,1436,203,1771]" captionTargetPageId="15" captionText="FIGURES 55–76. Anthaxia, aedeagi (not in scale). 55—Anthaxia (Anthaxia) candens (Panzer); 56—A. (A.) kmoniceki Bílý; 57—A. (Melanthaxia) nigrojubata incognita Bílý; 58—A. (M.) helvetica Stierlin; 59—A. (M.) obesa Abeille; 60—A. (Cratomerus) hungarica hungarica (Scopoli); 61—A. (Richteraxia) angustipennis (Klug); 62—A. (R.) crassa Obenberger; 63—A. (R.) imperatrix Obenberger; 64—A. (Haplanthaxia) elaeagni Richter; 65—A. (H.) nigroaenea Bílý; 66—A. (H.) pseudocongregata Descarpentries; 67—A. (H.) kneuckeri zabranskyi Bílý; 68—A. (H.) deimos Bílý; 69—A. (H.) dispar Kerremans; 70—A. (H.) loebli Bílý; 71—A. (H.) thailandica Bílý; 72—A. (H.) occulta Bílý; 73—A. (H.) duodevicesima Bílý; 74—A. (Merocratus) longipilis Bílý; 75—A. (Thailandica) rondoni; 76—A. (Capanthaxia) capensis Kerremans." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/2599430/files/figure.png" pageId="5" pageNumber="266">Figs. 69</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="2576369FFFD9E67ECF8FFF413065FEAF" blockId="6.[151,1436,151,320]" pageId="6" pageNumber="267">
The largest subgenus of the genus 
<taxonomicName id="E2C94D1CFFD9E67ECD0FFF4130FFFF5F" authorityName="Bílý" authorityYear="2019" box="[583,684,151,176]" class="Insecta" family="Buprestidae" genus="Anthaxia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="6" pageNumber="267" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="17BDEA8DFFD9E67ECD0FFF4130FFFF5F" box="[583,684,151,176]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="267">Anthaxia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
comprising about 70 % of all species. Many species-groups should be defined, and the subgenus should be revised group by group. Due to its world-wide distribution and an extreme similarity of some species it belongs among the taxonomically most difficult groups in 
<taxonomicName id="E2C94D1CFFD9E67ECB2AFF0936BFFF17" authorityName="Leach" authorityYear="1815" box="[1122,1260,223,248]" class="Insecta" family="Buprestidae" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="6" pageNumber="267" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="family">Buprestidae</taxonomicName>
. It is interesting that all species of 
<taxonomicName id="E2C94D1CFFD9E67ECE2DFED23399FEF2" authorityName="Bílý" authorityYear="2019" box="[357,458,260,285]" class="Insecta" family="Buprestidae" genus="Anthaxia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="6" pageNumber="267" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="17BDEA8DFFD9E67ECE2DFED23399FEF2" box="[357,458,260,285]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="267">Anthaxia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
distributed in 
<collectingCountry id="5DDE760FFFD9E67ECD38FED230A4FEF2" box="[624,759,260,285]" name="Madagascar" pageId="6" pageNumber="267">Madagascar</collectingCountry>
belongs only to this subgenus, but without any relationship to the fauna of the African continent.
</paragraph>
